  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the chances of finding work as a Non-EU Citizen after completing Master's Degree in Austria?",
  "response": "Finding work in Austria as a non-EU citizen after completing a Master's degree can vary based on several factors. Here's a general overview that might help you understand your chances:\n\n1. **Field of Study**: Certain fields have higher demand for professionals. STEM (Science, Technology, Engineering, Mathematics) and IT graduates tend to have better employment prospects.\n\n2. **Language Skills**: Proficiency in German significantly increases job opportunities. While many international companies and startup environments might use English, many local businesses require German.\n\n3. **Networking**: Establishing connections during your studies through internships, university events, and networking platforms can facilitate job opportunities. Austrian culture values personal connections and references.\n\n4. **University Reputation**: Graduating from a well-known Austrian university may improve your chances. Institutions like the University of Vienna, Graz University of Technology, and Vienna University of Economics and Business have strong reputations.\n\n5. **Austrian Red-White-Red Card**: Austria has specific immigration policies for skilled workers. The Red-White-Red Card is designed for highly qualified workers and can ease the process of staying and working in Austria. Make sure to check if you qualify.\n\n6. **Industry Connections**: Engage with professional industry associations and chambers of commerce which may have programs supporting non-EU graduates.\n\n7. **Career Services**: Utilize the career services of your university, which often provides support, job fairs, and partnerships with businesses.\n\n8. **Job Market Conditions**: Stay updated on the current job market conditions, unemployment rates, and economic outlook as these factors affect the availability of jobs.\n\n9. **Work Experience**: Having relevant work experience, internships, or practical projects done during your studies can make a big difference.\n\n10. **Visa Regulations**: Be aware of the visa regulations and the options for non-EU graduates. The process can be complex, but understanding it will help streamline your transition from student to employee.\n\nOverall, the chances can be quite reasonable if you equip yourself with the right skills, language proficiency, and industry knowledge. Adapting proactively to Austria's job market needs will enhance your employment prospects.",
